content.content: Inherited from Middle French prendre, from Old French prendre, prandre, from Latin prēndere, alternative form of prehendere (“to seize”), present active infinitive of prehendō, from prae- (“before”) + *hendō (“to take, seize”) (not attested without prefix), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰed-.
Je vais prendre le plat du jour.
I'll get the dish of the day.

content: to catch, to work, to start

content.content: ça ne prend pas avec moi
je me suis pris la main dans la porte
I caught my hand in the door
je me suis pris la porte dans la figure
the door hit me in the face

content: (in various idiomatic expressions) to start having a negative feeling towards someone

content.content: Qu’est-ce qui t’a pris ? Qu’est-ce qui t’est passé par la tête ?
What were you thinking? What got into you? What came over you?
Qu’est-ce qui lui a pris ? Quelle mouche l’a piqué ?
What was he thinking? What got into him?
good for him; it was a good choice (literally, “he took it well”)
too bad for him; it was a bad choice (literally, “he took it badly”)

content: (followed by a partitive, in various idiomatic expressions) to gain

content.content: to fall behind schedule, to run late, to drop behind
prendre de la brioche, prendre du bide, prendre du ventre

content: (colloquial; impersonal) to take (a certain amount of time)

content.content: Ça va me prendre au moins deux heures pour le mettre à jour.
It's going to take me at least two hours to update it.

content: (colloquial; impersonal; by extension) to take (a certain number or amount of)

content.content: Pour finir dans deux heures, ça prend trois personnes.
To finish in two hours, it'll take three people.

content: to come over (to arise in and gain some control over one's thoughts and/or actions)

content.content: Il lui prend une fantaisie de mettre le feu à la maison.
A fancy comes over him to set fire to the house.
Et s’il me prend l’envie d’ m’en aller, enferme-moi et jette la clé.
And if I feel like leaving, lock me up and throw away the key.
Inherited from Middle French sembler, from Old French sembler, from Late Latin similāre, a verb based on Latin similis (“similar”). Doublet of simuler.
Il semblerait qu’il y ait des différences significatives entre les deux groupes.
There would seem to be significant differences between the two groups.

Inherited from Old French chambre, cambre, from Latin cambra, Medieval spelling of Latin camera (“room”), from Ancient Greek καμάρα (kamára, “something with an arched cover: a covered wagon, a covered boat, a vaulted chamber”). Doublet of caméra, a borrowing.

content: a chamber in its various senses, including:

content.content: Oui, je suis d’accord avec vous.
to reach an agreement, to agree
